  "prompt": "Who are some great but lesser known female Indian freedom fighters?",
  "response": "Certainly! Here are some lesser-known yet remarkable female Indian freedom fighters who played significant roles in India's struggle for independence:\n\n1. **Aruna Asaf Ali** - Known for hoisting the Indian National Congress flag during the Quit India Movement at the Gowalia Tank Maidan in Bombay in 1942. She was a prominent leader in the movement and later became the first mayor of Delhi.\n\n2. **Usha Mehta** - A freedom fighter who helped set up Congress Radio, an underground radio station, during the Quit India Movement, which was used to disseminate news and messages among freedom fighters.\n\n3. **Sucheta Kriplani** - A close associate of Mahatma Gandhi, she was actively involved in the Quit India Movement and later went on to become the first female Chief Minister of an Indian state (Uttar Pradesh).\n\n4. **Kamaladevi Chattopadhyay** - A social reformer, freedom fighter, and the first woman to run for a legislative seat in India. She was also instrumental in revitalizing Indian handicrafts and handlooms.\n\n5. **Captain Lakshmi Sahgal** - A revolutionary leader of the Indian National Army (INA) founded by Subhas Chandra Bose. She was the head of the Rani of Jhansi Regiment, the women's regiment of the INA.\n\n6. **Sarojini Naidu** - Also known as the \"Nightingale of India,\" she was a key figure in the civil disobedience movement, a poet, and the first woman to become the President of the Indian National Congress and to serve as a governor in independent India.\n\n7. **Durgawati Devi** - Also known as \"Durga Bhabhi,\" she was an associate of Bhagat Singh and helped him and Rajguru escape after the killing of Saunders by driving them from Lahore to Lucknow.\n\n8. **Bina Das** - A revolutionary and a member of the Chhatri Sangha, she attempted to assassinate the Governor of Bengal and was subsequently imprisoned.\n\n9. **Matangini Hazra** - Affectionately known as \"Gandhi Buri,\" she was a part of the Quit India Movement and was shot dead by the British police while leading an advance on the Tamluk Police Station.\n\n10. **Annie Besant** - Although of British origin, she was a prominent supporter of Indian self-rule and campaigned for Theosophy and women's rights while connecting with Indian freedom fighters.\n\nThese women, through their determined and courageous actions, made invaluable contributions to India\u2019s quest for freedom, inspiring generations to come.",
